## How Student Cards Build Credit

**What helps your score:**
✅ On-time payments (35% of score—most important)
✅ Low credit utilization (under 30% of limit)
✅ Length of credit history (starts now)
✅ Diverse credit mix (credit cards count)

**What hurts your score:**
❌ Late payments (even 1 day late)
❌ Maxing out your card
❌ Applying for too many cards at once
❌ Closing your oldest account

**Credit-building timeline:**
- Month 1-6: Score 600-650 (building from scratch)
- Month 6-12: Score 650-700 (consistent on-time payments)
- Month 12-24: Score 700-750 (ready for premium cards)

## Smart Student Card Strategies

**1. Start small, prove responsible**
- Request low limit ($500-1,000) initially
- Pay in full every month (never carry a balance)
- Request credit limit increase after 6 months

**2. Set up autopay**
- Link checking account
- Auto-pay full statement balance
- Never miss a payment = perfect score foundation

**3. Track spending**
- Use card for recurring subscriptions (Spotify, Netflix)
- Pay off immediately
- Builds payment history without risk

**4. Avoid common mistakes**
- Don't use card for spring break trips you can't afford
- Don't max out limit (even if you can pay it off)
- Don't apply for store cards (focus on 1-2 quality cards)

## Student Card Approval Tips

**What helps approval:**
- Enrolled in 4-year college/university
- Proof of income ($500+/month from job, scholarships, or parental allowance)
- U.S. citizenship or permanent residency
- Age 18+ (or 21+ with no cosigner under CARD Act)

**Income sources that count:**
- Part-time job wages
- Internship pay
- Scholarships/financial aid
- Regular parental support (legally allowed under CARD Act)

**Don't lie about income—it's fraud and cards verify.**

## Secured vs. Unsecured Student Cards

**Unsecured (no deposit):**
All cards listed above require no security deposit—just enrollment proof.

**Secured (requires deposit):**
If denied for unsecured:
- Discover it® Secured Card ($200 deposit = $200 limit)
- Automatically reviewed for upgrade to unsecured

**When to use secured:** Credit score below 600 or international student with no U.S. credit history.

